==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wicca
<hw>Wic"ca</hw> <pr>(w⟦icr⟧k"k⟦adot⟧)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos>
<ety>[OE. <ets>wicche</ets> wizard, AS. <ets>wicce</ets>, fem.,
<ets>wicca</ets>, masc.; see also <er>witch</er> and
<er>wicked</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A religion derived from
pre-Christian times, also called <altname>Witchcraft</altname>{4}, which
practices a benevolent reverence for nature, and recognizes two deities,
variously viewed as Mother & Father, Goddess & God, Female & Male, etc.;
its practitioners are called Wiccans, Wiccas, or witches. Since there is
no central authority to propagate dogma, the beliefs and practices of
Wiccans vary significantly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>Encouraged by court rulings recognizing witchcraft as a legal
religion, an increasing number of books related to the subject, and the
continuing cultural concern for the environment, <ex>Wicca</ex> -- as
contemporary witchcraft is often called -- has been growing in the
United States and abroad. It is a major element in the expanding
⟦ldquo⟧neo-pagan⟦rdquo⟧ movement whose members regard nature itself as
charged with divinity.</q> <rj><qau>Gustav Niebuhr (N. Y. Times, Oct.
31, 1999, p. 1)</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>⟦ldquo⟧I don't worship Satan, who I don't think exists, but I do
pray to the Goddess of Creation.⟦rdquo⟧ said <person>Margot S.
Adler</person>, a New York correspondent for National Public Radio and a
<ex>Wiccan</ex> practitioner. ⟦ldquo⟧<ex>Wicca</ex> is not
anti-Christian or pro-Christian, it's pre-Christian.⟦rdquo⟧</q>
<rj><qau>Anthony Ramirez (N. Y. Times Aug. 22, 1999, p. wk
2)</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note> <ex>Wicca</ex> is a ditheistic religion, also called
Witchcraft, founded on the beliefs and doctrines of pre-Roman Celts,
including the reverence for nature and the belief in a universal
balance. Though frequently practiced in covens, solitary practitioners
do exist. The modern form of the religion was popularized in 1954 by
<person>Gerald Gardener's</person> <booki>Witchcraft Today</booki>. It
is viewed as a form of neo-paganism.⟦br⟧
Wicca recognizes two deities, visualized as Mother & Father, Goddess &
God, Female & Male, etc. These dieties are nameless, but many Wiccans
adopt a name with which they refer to the two: Diana is a popular name
for the Goddess to take, among others such as Artemis, Isis, Morrigan,
etc. Some of her symbols are: the moon; the ocean; a cauldron; and the
labrys (two-headed axe), among others. The God is of equal power to the
Goddess, and takes on names such as Apollo, Odin, Lugh, etc. A small
number of his symbols are: the sun; the sky; a horn (or two horns); and
others.⟦br⟧
Witchcraft is not a Christian denomination; there is no devil in its
mythos, thus the devil cannot be worshiped, and the medieval view of
Witches as Satan-worshipers is erroneous. Satanists are not Witches and
Witches are not Satanists. Both have a tendency to be offended when the
two are confused.⟦br⟧
In the Wiccan religion male Witches are not ⟦ldquo⟧Warlocks⟦rdquo⟧. The
term Warlock comes from Scottish, meaning 'oathbreaker', 'traitor', or
'devil'. Its application to male witches is of uncertain origin.⟦br⟧
The Wiccan Rede, ⟦ldquo⟧An it harm none, do what thou wilt⟦rdquo⟧ comes
in many variations. All of them say the same thing, ⟦ldquo⟧Do as you
wish, just don't do anything to harm anyone.⟦rdquo⟧ It is implied that
'anyone' includes one's self.⟦br⟧
Witches practice in groups called Covens or as solitary practitioners,
and some practice ⟦ldquo⟧magic⟦rdquo⟧, which is to say, they pray. Since
the one rule that Witches have requires that they can not do harm,
harmful magic does not exist in Wicca. In Wicca, ⟦ldquo⟧magic⟦rdquo⟧ is
simply subtly altering small things, to gain a desired effect.⟦br⟧
Wicca, sometimes called Neo-Witchcraft, was revived in the 1950s, when
the last laws against Witchcraft were repealed. <person>Gerald
Gardner</person> founded Gardnerian Wicca sometime after his book,
<booki>Witchcraft Today</booki>, was published in 1954. <person>Raymond
Buckland</person>, in America, did much the same that Gardner did in
Europe -- stood up to the misconceptions about Witchcraft.⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
Two other books describing the modern practice of Wicca are:⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
<booki>Wicca: A Guide for the Solitary Practitioner</booki>, by
<person>Scott Cunningham</person>, Llewellyn Publications, 1988.⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
<booki>Buckland's Complete Book of Witchcraft</booki>, by
<person>Raymond Buckland</person>, Llewellyn Publications, 1975.⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
A Web site devoted to elucidation of modern witchcraft is:⟦br⟧
<a href="http://www.witchvox.com">Witchvox</a></note> <rj><au>Cody
Scott</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A practitioner of Wicca, also commonly called a
<altname>Wiccan</altname>, <altname>Wicca</altname>, or
<altname>witch</altname> .</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>For at least one person who has seen ⟦ldquo⟧The Blair Witch
Project⟦rdquo⟧, the surprise hit movie of the summer did not so much
terrify as infuriate. One long slur against witches, said <person>Selena
Fox</person>, a witch, or <ex>Wicca</ex>, as male and female American
witches prefer to call themselves.</q> <rj><qau>Anthony Ramirez (N. Y.
Times, Aug. 22, 1999, p. wk 2)</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wiccan</ent>⟦br⟧
